<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Freightliner Group (SRN 003)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><br /></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Written e</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">vidence from Freightliner Group (SRN 003)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span><br /></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Freightliner Group (Freightliner) is pleased to provide evidence to the Transport Committee Inquiry into the Strategic Road Network.</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Freightliner is a logistics company who specialises in moving goods by rail with a modern fleet of rolling stock and road vehicles. We are the second largest rail freight operator in the UK (approximately 38% market share) and specialise in moving deep-se</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">a containers from major ports to inland terminals and onward delivery by road to customers. Freightliner moves 1 in 5 of all deep-sea containers transported in the UK, as well as approximately 20 million tonnes of bulk goods. We have established ourselves </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">as a leader within the rail freight industry, not only in the UK, but in Europe and Australia.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">In the context of this Inquiry, we note that many of our customers are also active road freight operators and users.  Our response does not cover any specific p</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">oints on the strategic road network other than where there is relationship with rail freight.</span><br /></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">General Comments </span><br /></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">For customers and operators in the road and rail freight sector the different modes are viewed as being in competition.  For specific movement</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">s there is little doubt that this is the case, with road and rail competing for traffic on cost and on service quality.  Rail freight must equal or better road costs if it is to win and retain business.</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">From a national perspective, and in consideration of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> the provision of new infrastructure, it is necessary to consider how freight can be moved most efficiently for the overall benefit of the UK.  We believe that this requires each mode to be developed to play to its particular strengths and that the develop</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ment of each mode is considered in parallel when looking at particular interventions.</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Many of the measures in the Strategic Roads White Paper may be reasonable but there is little evidence that they have been considered as part of an overall national stra</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">tegy for efficient freight movement considering all modes holistically.  </span><br /></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Specific Questions</span><br /></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q2 </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> does the Government</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">’</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?</span><br /></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">We are pleased that the Highways Agency is starting to develop route</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> based strategies for the strategic road network.  This approach has worked well for the rail industry with the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> of Route </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Utilisation</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> Strategies developed over the last ten years.  </span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">However we believe that there should be much closer alignment of</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> the development of route based strategies and investment in the rail network. This would allow consideration of how investment in rail could help to meet the demands of the road corridor and also highlight where investment in roads might in some cases und</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ermine the case for modal switch to rail without any compensating measures.</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 15.7pt; padding-left:2.3pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">This approach was used to some extent on the A14 corridor where the research studies showed how investment in the parallel rail corridor could help accommodate some of the predict</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ed </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">H</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">GV growth.  The Atkins A14 Study Output 3 report stated that </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS'; font-size:10pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">planned investment in rail </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">route from </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Felixstowe</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> could cut HGV traffic on A14 by 11%, which is 60-80% of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">forecast growth in HGVs</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS'; font-size:10pt">”</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The worked helped to support the case for investment i</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">n the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Felixstowe</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Nuneaton</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> rail corridor for which, further investment was confirmed in the 2012 High Level Output Specification, and is expected to be delivered over the next five years.</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Therefore we would urge for more cross-modal assessment to be und</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ertaken in the development of the route strategies including the A1 and Trans-</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Pennine</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> routes where study work is already under development.</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Freightliner is also concerned that much of the current initiatives being progressed by </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> are </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">focused</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> on the long distance road haulage of goods, where rail freight is better able to compete with road.  Instead, we consider developments may be better targeted at areas where road haulage has a natural monopoly, such as specific deliveries and access away f</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">rom the main trunk rail network, i.e. a focus on a modally integrated approach</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">An example of this is the longer semi-trailer trial, presently underway, which targets the long distance market in particular, and will make it more difficult for rail to compe</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">te.  </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS'; font-size:10pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> own assessment suggested that around 27% to 32% of the environmental benefits of longer trailers are assumed to be gained by running fewer trains. By 2025, 84% of the industry operational savings would be from lower rail costs.  In other words, </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">a significant proportion of the benefit cited from longer semi</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">trailers come at the expense of rail freight.  </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> are now progressing research into 10 lorry convoys </span><span style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS'; font-size:10pt">–</span><span style="font-family:'Arial Unicode MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">yet the average train removes 60 </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">lorries</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> from the road network.</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> is also reviewing th</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">e rail freight grant scheme - MSRS, which exists to balance the different costs of road and rail freight where the environmental benefits justify mode switch.  The de- facto grant rate has fallen significantly since the scheme was introduced as rail has im</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">proved; its efficiency and productivity, network investment has been progressed and economies of scale have arisen.  However, particularly for growing domestic traffic in the retail sector, and shorter distance intermodal port traffic the need for grant is</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> expected to remain, and we will be urging Government to ensure that the scheme continues and is appropriately funded.  Measures such as longer semi- trailers also perpetuate the need for grant.</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Freightliner recognizes that the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">DfT</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> has provided investment</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> in the rail network in support of rail freight and that all modes need to progress and seek efficiencies, but there should be a balanced approach to enable the most efficient and environmentally friendly solution for the UK.</span><br /></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q4 </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">How</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> can we improve the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">reliability and efficiency of travel on the strategic road network? What impact will new technology have?</span><br /></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Encouraging a greater use of rail freight will have benefits for the strategic road network.  We note, for example, the proposed studies of lorry con</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">voys of up to 10 </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">lorries</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, yet the average freight train can take 60 lorries off the road.  Encouraging rail freight can also help improve road safety again by removing </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">lorries</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> from the road.</span><br /></li><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Rail freight is acknowledged as having a superior environmental </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">performance, producing around 70% less carbon dioxide than the equivalent journey by road.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Q6 </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">What</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold"> mechanisms are there for Government to increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries t</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">hat could be applied in the UK? </span><br /></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">The new HGV charge applied to foreign registered </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">hauliers</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> is unlikely to make a significant financial contribution to UK road funding.  Freightliner would support a longer term move to a distance based charge, which is com</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">mon in other EU countries, which would provide the right incentives for mode shift encourage reductions in road miles and more closely aligns the charging structure for road and rail. Charges for rail freight operators are set by the Office of Rail Regulat</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ion (ORR)</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">, which </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">has expressed its desire to set charges for rail freight on the basis of economic incentives and they are therefore becoming increasingly complex and uncertain</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">(reviewed every 5 years). </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">Meanwhile the </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">road</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> haulage industry</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> pays </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">only </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">fuel du</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">ty</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> and vehicle excise duty</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> which is extremely simple</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> the level of </span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">duty</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> is set</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt"> by Government in a political context</span><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Trebuchet MS'; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>